1 Statitical modeling

Given the use of multiple CAL measures in our study, our candidate statistical model, which was fit using the nlme package in R, included several characteristics.

First, the model assumed that CAL measures used in our study were a random sample of a larger set of possible CAL measures available in the literature. As a result, CAL measures were considered to be random-effects for each participant across all the participants.

Second, these CAL measure random-effects were found to be non-overlapping (uncorrelated) with one another for each participant across all the participants.

Third, the CAL measure random-effects seemed to have varying amounts of variation in them (i.e., were heterogeneous) for each participant across all the participants (\(\tau\) in the model characteristics tables).

Fourth, although the random-effects seemed to be uncorrelated, the residuals of the model (i.e., variation in CAL scores the model couldn’t explain) seemed to be slightly correlated common to each participant across all the participants (\(\rho\) in the model characteristics tables).

Finally, in addition to their correlation, the variation in the residuals of the model seemed to differ across different CAL measures as well as different times of CAL measurement (\(\sigma\) in the model characteristics tables).

This level of flexibility allowed the model to accommodate the various types of CAL measures, differences in their scales of measurement, as well as violations of their underlying distributional assumptions (e.g., normality).

In the tables to follow, these model characteristics will also be quantified and displayed separately for each research question.
